SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>3/15/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>1:28:19 pm</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">** NEWS ** 03/15/01</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial"><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><center> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> NO CHANGE TO THE OLD</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></center><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Source: EverQuest General Discussion Forums.<br>
<br>
I just wanted to pop in here and let you all know that the plan for such code changes, like the 'Trivial Combat' code idea, is to go forward with them. It is unlikely that we'll move that code or others like it back into the existing game. <br>
The plan is to try the idea out and see how it works. We want to know what you think of it (after trying it out) and then decide if we will include the code in future content. Yes, there is a very small chance that we'll find some code that is so overwhelmingly great that we'll use it in the old world. But we will be reluctant to do so because gauging the impact of a change like that on old content would be all but impossible. <br>
<br>
- Alan</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Alan then responded to some player statements regarding the new code: <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The newbie actually does have the ability (in game code) to go wherever he wants and loot any mob that he kills. The difference is that the newbie does not yet have the necessary skill to do that. If he/she were twinked enough, he/she could then kill and loot mobs way out of his/her class range.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> If you want to argue specifics, the high level character can also go wherever he wants and loot any mob that he kills. That ability is not restricted by code either. <br>
<br>
But this is just a semantics argument, and it avoids the point.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> The argument is with the capability involved. By removing the capability from the higher class player through coding you have removed something that you've technically paid for. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The game is set up so that a low level character just can't do certain things. It is set up so that if you play a High Elf there's a good chance you will never get to do some quests in Oggok. There are all kinds of restrictions on what a character can and can't do. Having paid $10 does not mean that you will get to see all the content all the time. If a new player wants to help defeat Naggy, he's going to have to level his character. If a player with a high level character wants loot off of a low level NPC in The Warrens, he's going to have to do it with a low level character. <br>
<br>
Saying that this rule somehow restricts the player of a high level characters is misleading. Every player has the exact same access to all content as any other player. <br>
<br>
- Alan </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
